Xavier's Technical Institute,Old Building, Ground Floor,Mahim Causeway, Mahim (W),Mumbai - 400 016IndiaTel: +91-22-2446 3565 / 66 +91-99-3089 39994.21CREW HEALTH, WELFARE AND RETENTION4.21.1MEDICAL EXAMINATIONA candidate joining the Company for the first time shall undergo a pre-employment medical by an approved medical practitioner. Thismedical examination shall be carried out as per ILO / Flag administration and fitness certificates shall be issued in their prescribedform.A crew member rejoining Company vessels shall have an ILO / Flag State medical which is valid for a minimum period of the intendedcontract duration + 1 month. In no case shall a Medical certificate have a validity of more than 2 years.Seafarers that have been refused a certificate or have had a limitation imposed on their ability to work, in particular with respect totime, field of work, or trading area, shall be given the opportunity to have a further examination by any other company doctor or dulyqualified independent practitioner.All personnel shall be medically screened for drug and alcohol abuse and HIV during the medical examination. Drugs tested will be in accordance with OCIMFguidelines.Declaration by seafarers: Each seafarer is required to declare his medical condition truthfully prior joining the vessel.Following personnel shall undergo stress test as part of the medical examination:1. Officers above 50 years of age2. Ratings above 45 years of ageChest X-ray and Ultrasonography shall be carried out for all officers and ratings, during the medical examination.The seafarers shall also undergo mental health counseling, should they be subject to a situation involving hostage taking or piracyaboard a vessel or other situations as required.The frequency of medical checks is clearly defined and complied with across the company to meet appropriate legislation.4.21.2HEALTH & HYGIENE AWARENESSThe company shall maintain high standards of housekeeping and hygiene on board ships. These standards carry special emphasis onfood storage and preparation. HSEQA Bulletin will also be used as a medium to disseminate information to crew on lifestyle, healthydiet, exercise and health related issues.4.21.3CREW WELFARECompany policy places importance on creating and fostering a healthy living and working environment for its seafarers while onboardship.Section 6 and Annex 4 of The “Health, Safety, Environment and Quality Assurance (HSEQA) Manual” and “Section 5 of the“Vessel Operations Manual” identify the standards to be maintained of crew welfare items such as quality of food, standard of theaccommodation, rest and recreation facilities, hygiene, air conditioning, access to medical attention, and shore leave when shipoperations and port regulations allow.4.21.4RETENTION RATE OF OFFICERS AND RATINGSThe company shall endeavor best to retain its ship-board personnel and also monitor retention rates achieved for different ranks andnationalities. If the retention rate of ship-board senior officers drops below the defined KPI reasons for same shall be evaluated andnecessary preventive measures taken.When senior officers resign, the company shall endeavor to obtain feedback in order to ascertain reasons for same. Any negativetrends identified shall be discussed in the Annual Management Review (AMR) meetings.4.22FAMILY CARRIAGE
